   "id": "part9-header",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Part 9: Prompt Engineering & Agent Reliability\n",
    "\n",
    "This is the part most workshops skip — and it's the reason most agents fail in production.\n",
    "\n",
    "> **The core problem:** An agent built on GPT-4o with a weak prompt will be\n",
    "> outperformed by an agent on GPT-4o-mini with an engineered prompt.\n",
    "> Prompt quality is your most cost-effective lever.\n",
    "\n",
    "### The Five Techniques We'll Cover\n",
    "\n",
    "| # | Technique | What it solves |\n",
    "|---|---|---|\n",
    "| 1 | **Output Format Enforcement** | Agent deviates from Thought/Action format → parser crashes |\n",
    "| 2 | **Role + Constraint Framing** | Agent goes off-topic or speculates without evidence |\n",
    "| 3 | **Few-Shot Examples** | Inconsistent output structure across different models |\n",
    "| 4 | **Structured Output Parsing** | Can't use agent output downstream (in databases, Slack, etc.) |\n",
    "| 5 | **Prompt Versioning** | Can't track what changed when reliability degrades |"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "part9-imports",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import sys\n",
    "sys.path.insert(0, '..')\n",
    "\n",
    "from agent.prompt_engineering import (\n",
    "    PROMPT_V1_WEAK,\n",
    "    PROMPT_V2_FORMAT_ENFORCED,\n",
    "    PROMPT_V3_ROLE_CONSTRAINED,\n",
    "    PROMPT_V4_FEW_SHOT,\n",
    "    PROMPT_REGISTRY,\n",
    "    get_prompt,\n",
    "    parse_agent_output,\n",
    "    format_assessment_for_display,\n",
    "    RiskAssessment,\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "print('✅ Prompt engineering module loaded')\n",
    "print(f'   Available prompt versions: {list(PROMPT_REGISTRY.keys())}')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "part9-technique1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Technique 1: Output Format Enforcement\n",
    "\n",
    "Run the two cells below. The first shows a weak prompt — the second shows what format enforcement looks like.\n",
    "\n",
    "Read the difference carefully. The key additions are:\n",
    "- `You MUST use EXACTLY this format — never deviate`\n",
    "- Tool names embedded directly in the Action line\n",
    "- `do NOT write this yourself` on the Observation line\n",
    "- A structured schema for Final Answer"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "part9-weak-prompt",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Read the weak prompt — notice what's missing\n",
    "print('=== V1: WEAK PROMPT ===')\n",
    "print(PROMPT_V1_WEAK.template)\n",
    "print()\n",
    "print('Problems with this prompt:')\n",
    "print('  ✗ No format instructions — LLM will sometimes skip tools entirely')\n",
    "print('  ✗ No output schema — output is unparseable')\n",
    "print('  ✗ No constraints — agent will speculate freely')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "part9-strong-prompt",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Read the engineered prompt — spot each improvement\n",
    "print('=== V2: FORMAT ENFORCED ===')\n",
    "print(PROMPT_V2_FORMAT_ENFORCED.template)\n",
    "print()\n",
    "print('Improvements:')\n",
    "print('  ✅ \"You MUST use EXACTLY this format\" — direct, non-negotiable')\n",
    "print('  ✅ Tool names in the Action line — agent knows its options')\n",
    "print('  ✅ Structured Final Answer — SEVERITY / SUMMARY / RECOMMENDATION')\n",
    "print('  ✅ Observation note — prevents the agent from hallucinating results')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "part9-technique2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Technique 2: Role + Constraint Framing\n",
    "\n",
    "Compare V2 and V3 below. The difference is in the identity and rules you give the agent.\n",
    "\n",
    "> **Key Insight:** \"You are a supply chain analyst\" is a job title.\n",
    "> \"You are a Supply Chain Risk Analyst at a Canadian manufacturing company\n",
    "> and your constraints are...\" is a job description. The second version\n",
    "> produces dramatically more focused outputs."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "part9-constraints",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "print('=== V3: ROLE + CONSTRAINTS ===')\n",
    "print(PROMPT_V3_ROLE_CONSTRAINED.template)\n",
    "print()\n",
    "print('What the constraints do:')\n",
    "print('  ✅ Constraint 3: \"If no results, say so\" — prevents hallucination')\n",
    "print('  ✅ Constraint 4: Scope limiting — agent stays on topic')\n",
    "print('  ✅ CONFIDENCE field — agent signals its own uncertainty')\n",
    "print()\n",
    "print('WORKSHOP EXERCISE:')\n",
    "print('  Add a constraint: \"Never mention competitor company names in your output.\"')\n",
    "print('  Test whether the agent follows it.')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "part9-technique3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Technique 3: Few-Shot Examples\n",
    "\n",
    "A few-shot example is a complete, correct response that you paste into the prompt\n",
    "before the real question. It shows the agent *exactly* what you expect.\n",
    "\n",
    "This is the most reliable technique for getting consistent output format,\n",
    "especially on smaller/cheaper models."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "part9-fewshot",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "print('=== V4: FEW-SHOT EXAMPLE ADDED ===')\n",
    "print(PROMPT_V4_FEW_SHOT.template)\n",
    "print()\n",
    "print('Token cost estimate for the example alone:')\n",
    "example_tokens = len(PROMPT_V4_FEW_SHOT.template) // 4  # rough estimate\n",
    "print(f'  ~{example_tokens} tokens')\n",
    "print(f'  At GPT-4o-mini rates (~$0.00015/1K tokens): ~${example_tokens * 0.00015 / 1000:.6f} per call')\n",
    "print()\n",
    "print('WORKSHOP DISCUSSION:')\n",
    "print('  Q: Is that cost worth it for consistent, parseable output?')\n",
    "print('  Q: When would you NOT use few-shot? (High-volume, low-stakes queries)')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "part9-technique4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Technique 4: Parsing Structured Output\n",
    "\n",
    "Because we engineered the Final Answer to have a schema, we can now\n",
    "parse it into a Python object. This is what makes agent output usable\n",
    "by downstream systems.\n",
    "\n",
    "Run the cell below with different output strings — including a broken one —\n",
    "and observe how the parser handles each case."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "part9-parsing",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Simulate what a well-formed agent output looks like\n",
    "well_formed_output = \"\"\"\n",
    "SEVERITY: HIGH\n",
    "SUMMARY: The Port of Montreal is experiencing significant delays due to a labour\n",
    "dispute between dock workers and the St. Lawrence Seaway Management Corporation.\n",
    "Rail connections to Toronto and Montreal are backed up 4-5 days.\n",
    "RECOMMENDATION: Activate contingency routing through Halifax for all inbound\n",
    "European shipments for the next two weeks.\n",
    "CONFIDENCE: HIGH\n",
    "\"\"\"\n",
    "\n",
    "# Parse it\n",
    "assessment = parse_agent_output(well_formed_output)\n",
    "print('Parse result:')\n",
    "print(f'  severity:          {assessment.severity}')\n",
    "print(f'  confidence:        {assessment.confidence}')\n",
    "print(f'  parse_succeeded:   {assessment.parse_succeeded}')\n",
    "print(f'  summary[:60]:      {assessment.summary[:60]}...')\n",
    "print()\n",
    "print(format_assessment_for_display(assessment))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "part9-parsing-broken",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Now test with a broken output (what V1 prompt produces)\n",
    "broken_output = \"\"\"\n",
    "Based on my research, I found that there are some potential risks in the supply\n",
    "chain. The situation at ports is complex and there may be delays. I would recommend\n",
    "monitoring the situation closely and staying in touch with your suppliers.\n",
    "\"\"\"\n",
    "\n",
    "broken_assessment = parse_agent_output(broken_output)\n",
    "print('Parse result for broken output:')\n",
    "print(f'  severity:          {broken_assessment.severity}  ← defaults to UNKNOWN')\n",
    "print(f'  parse_succeeded:   {broken_assessment.parse_succeeded}  ← False means we cannot use this downstream')\n",
    "print()\n",
    "print('WORKSHOP TAKEAWAY:')\n",
    "print('  A parse failure is not just an annoyance — it means the output')\n",
    "print('  cannot be stored in a database, sent to Slack in a structured way,')\n",
    "print('  or used to trigger downstream workflows.')\n",
    "print('  Prompt engineering IS reliability engineering.')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "part9-technique5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Technique 5: Prompt Versioning\n",
    "\n",
    "Prompts must be treated like code. When reliability drops, you need to know\n",
    "which version is running, what changed, and when.\n",
    "\n",
    "The `PROMPT_REGISTRY` in `prompt_engineering.py` is a simple implementation\n",
    "of this pattern. In production, you'd store this in a database or a version-\n",
    "controlled YAML file."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "part9-versioning",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Inspect the prompt registry\n",
    "print('PROMPT VERSION HISTORY')\n",
    "print('=' * 55)\n",
    "for version, pv in PROMPT_REGISTRY.items():\n",
    "    print(f'\\n{pv.version} ({pv.added_date})')\n",
    "    print(f'  Description: {pv.description}')\n",
    "    if pv.known_failure_modes:\n",
    "        print(f'  Known issues:')\n",
    "        for issue in pv.known_failure_modes:\n",
    "            print(f'    - {issue}')\n",
    "\n",
    "print()\n",
    "print('WORKSHOP EXERCISE:')\n",
    "print('  Add a v5 to the PROMPT_REGISTRY in prompt_engineering.py.')\n",
    "print('  Your v5 should add: a maximum response length constraint')\n",
    "print('  (\"Your SUMMARY must be 2 sentences maximum\") and note what')\n",
    "print('  problem it solves in the description field.')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "part9-live-comparison",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Live Comparison: V1 vs V4 on the Same Query\n",
